// ...
dp[400] = 549755813888
// ...
dp[500] = 562949953421312
// ...
dp[600] = 576460752303423488
```

Exponential growth! For `dp[600]`, we can dive in its computation:

```c++
dp[600] = + dp[0] + dp[10] + dp[20] + dp[30] + ... + dp[590]
= dp[0] + (dp[0] + dp[0]) + (dp[0] + dp[10] + dp[0]) + ... + (dp[0] + ... dp[580] + dp[0])
= 2 ^ 59
```

Finally, we need 99 bits to save `dp[990]` while `unsigned long long` have just 64 bits!

If they use this testcase:

```
[1,2]
1000
```

We need 100 bits to save `dp[1000]`! Of course, Leetcode guaranteed the answer to fit in a 32-bit integer.
So we just drop these too large numbers.

The reason `unsigned` works is Leetcode doesn't detect unsigned integer overflow.
If they use `-fsanitize=unsigned-integer-overflow`, `unsigned` solution would not pass.

Here is my AC solution:

```c++
int combinationSum4(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
	int dp[target + 1];
	dp[0] = 1;

	for (int i = 1; i <= target; ++i) {
		dp[i] = 0;
		for (auto v : nums) {
			if (i >= v && numeric_limits<int>::max() - dp[i - v] >= dp[i]) {
				dp[i] += dp[i - v];
			}
		}
	}

	return dp[target];
}
```

**Fatal Misunderstanding**

Recently I learnt about [VLA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variable-length_array). VLA is variable length array. It is supported in C99 but not in C++! so

```c++
int dp[target + 1];
```

is never right in C++. It is not stdandard C++! This code can be compiled by GCC and Clang but MSVC.

We should use

```c++
vector<int> dp(target + 1);
```

I have this misunderstanding for a long time. It makes me ashamed.

