# why signed not long long
Different type has different behavior. Signed integer (int or long long) in GCC will break as an error when overflowing. But unsigned integers will do the arithmetic as an modular operation (mod 4294967296=2^32) when overflowing. Since  LC says "The test cases are generated so that the answer can fit in a 32-bit integer." the final is correct whereas the intermediate values can be treated as the computed values modulo 4294967296=2^32!

