**Method 1:** Brute force
> **T/S:** O(n^t)/O(t), where n = size(nums) and t = target
```
public int combinationSum(int[] nums, int target) {
	return combinationSum(nums, target, 0);
}

private int combinationSum(int[] nums, int target, int sum) {
	if (sum > target)
		return 0;
	if (sum == target)
		return 1;

	var count = 0;
	for (var num : nums)
		count += combinationSum(nums, target, sum + num);
	return count;
}
```

**Method 2:** Inject memoization in method 1
> **T/S:** O(t)/O(t).
Because of memoization, no node in the decision tree will be calculated more than once. Each node will correspond to a number less than T that can be reached using options in nums. Using these 2 statements, time complexity would be O(T).
```
public int combinationSum(int[] nums, int target) {
	var dp = new int[target + 1];
	Arrays.fill(dp, -1);
	return combinationSum(nums, target, dp, 0);
}

private int combinationSum(int[] nums, int target, int[] dp, int sum) {
	if (sum > target)
		return 0;
	if (sum == target)
		return 1;
	if (dp[sum] != -1)
		return dp[sum];

	var count = 0;
	for (var num : nums)
		count += combinationSum(nums, target, dp, sum + num);
	return dp[sum] = count;
}
```

**Method 3:** Tabulation
> **T/S:** O(nT)/O(T)
```
public int combinationSum4(int[] nums, int target) {
	var dp = new int[target + 1];
	dp[0] = 1;
	var n = dp.length;

	for (var i = 0; i < n - 1; i++)
		for (var num : nums)
			if (i + num < n)
				dp[i + num] += dp[i];
	return dp[n - 1];
}
```
