# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The intuition behind the above solution is to use dynamic programming to count the number of ways to reach the target sum using the given numbers.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The approach is to create an array dp, where dp[i] represents the number of ways to reach the sum i using the numbers from the nums array. We initialize dp[0] to 1 because there is one way to reach the target sum of 0, which is by using no numbers.

The code then iterates through the target sum from 1 to the actual target value, and for each value, it iterates through the numbers in the nums array. For each number num, if i >= num, it means we can use that number to reach the sum i, so we add dp[i - num] to dp[i] to accumulate the number of ways.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of this solution is O(target * n), where n is the length of the nums array. We have a nested loop structure, where the outer loop iterates through the target values from 1 to the actual target, and the inner loop iterates through the nums array. In the worst case, this results in O(target * n) iterations.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is O(target + 1), which simplifies to O(target) because we only need an array of length target + 1 to store the dp values. This space is used to store the intermediate results of subproblems.

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public int CombinationSum4(int[] nums, int target) {
        int[] dp = new int[target + 1];
        dp[0] = 1; // There's one way to reach target 0, which is by using no numbers.

        for (int i = 1; i <= target; i++) {
            foreach (int num in nums) {
                if (i >= num) {
                    dp[i] += dp[i - num];
                }
            }
        }

        return dp[target];
    }
}
```

